chers and practitioners in six countries it examines critically how listening to young children in early childhood services is understood and practised. Each chapter is rooted in the everyday lives of young children and presents a range of actual experiences for students and practitioners to draw from. Beyond listening goes further to address key questions emerging from early childhood services and research. These are What do we mean by listening? Why listen? How do we listen to young children? What view of the child do different approaches to listening presume? What risks does listening entail for young children? The authors are leading experts in this area of rapidly growing interest and have themselves developed innovative methods such as the Mosaic approach, which is discussed in the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aCarr, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Alison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDriscoll, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEide, Brit Johanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinney, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKjørholt, Anne Trine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKjørholt, Anne Trine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoss, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https: